snippet: With ballots from all districts counted, the party led by President Jacob Zuma was only slightly down from its showing in 1994, the year it assumed power in the country’s first democratic election.
abstract: African National Congress wins 62 percent of vote in South Africa's fifth post-apartheid election, nearly same share it won in 1994; almost identical results mask glaring differences between the two periods, during which the party has been transformed from liberation movement to political party buffeted by corruption, popular disillusionment and widespread complaints.
lead_paragraph: With ballots from all districts counted, the party led by President Jacob Zuma was only slightly down from its showing in 1994, the year it assumed power in the country’s first democratic election.

headline.main: African National Congress Draws 62 Percent of the Vote in South Africa
headline.print_headline: African National Congress Draws 62 Percent of the Vote in South Africa
